<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1912-05-17T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1912-05-17T00:00:00-05:00" n="1507" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1507">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 817.51/451.</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">American Minister</gloss> to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi>.</head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 35.]</seg>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Managua</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-05-17">
                                    <hi rend="italic">May 17, 1912</hi></date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: Referring to my telegram of May 11, 11
                                a.m.,<note n="1" xml:id="d1507fn1">Not printed.</note> I have the
                            honor to enclose herewith a copy and translation of the measure<note n="1" xml:id="d1507fn2">Not printed.</note> passed by the National
                            Assembly authorizing the President of Nicaragua to make a settlement of
                            the Ethelburga loan.</p>
                        <p>In that same connection I enclose a copy<note n="1" xml:id="d1507fn3">Not
                                printed.</note> of a telegram given to me by the President, the
                            English text of which is probably already before the Department. It is
                            dated May 12, 1912, addressed by Brown Brothers to their local
                            representative, and contains the terms of the Ethelburga settlement, as
                            reported in my telegram of May 14, 4 p.m.<note n="1" xml:id="d1507fn4">Not printed.</note>
                        </p>
                        <p>I have [etc.]</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">George T. Weitzel.</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>